      <body>
         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne bot Garden, ¶ 25/4/73 ¶  ¶ The rest of the Monocotyledoneae with adnate Calyx-tube, dear Mr Bentham, was despatched under date 24 March by the Steamship  ¶ Somersetshire ¶ , and an other por...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">73.04.25</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1871-81, ff. 88-9.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Melbourne bot Garden,</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">25/4/73</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The rest of the <name key="Monocotyledoneae">Monocotyledoneae</name> with adnate Calyx-tube, dear Mr Bentham, was despatched under date 24 March by the Steamship <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Somersetshire</hi>
               </seg>, and an other portion on the 30 jan by the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Hampshire</hi>
               </seg> under care of Capt Ridgers. In that instance no bill of loading was got; so there is some risk! of loss, unless the Kew Agent has watched the arrival of the Ship.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I was inclined to send you the <name key="Liliaceae">Liliaceae</name> and allied orders, which are ready, by the Atrato; but not knowing, whether you really do require them, I though it better to wait for your next letter. For I might other wise be deprived of the use of the collections for a year or two without need, until the 7th vol<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Of <seg style="">Bentham (1863-78).</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> was in progress.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>During the Easter Holidays<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Easter fell on 13 April in 1873.</p>
               </note> I worked a little on plants, and commenced the 60th number of the fragmenta.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B73.04.02.</p>
               </note> I find that <name key="Donatia">Donatia</name> is a truly Stylideous plant, simply with its column dissolved and with its corolla deprived of a tube, having however the broad base of the petals (or segments) as in <name key="Galium">Galium</name> &amp;c. So there can not be the slightest doubt now, after what Dr Hooker already has written on the subject, that <name key="Donatia">Donatia</name> is Stylideous.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">J. Hooker (1844-7), vol. 1, part ii, pp. 281-2.</p>
               </note> I am likely to get ripe fruits from the Alps of Tasmania next month. This month the plant was still in flower.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Another interesting fact is the occurrence of <name key="Lagerstroemia%20Indica">Lagerstroemia Indica</name> in N.E. Australia. I found also, that <name key="Threlkeldia%20haloragoides">Threlkeldia haloragoides</name> is a new genus of Phytolacceae, as indicated by me several years ago. I sent the manuscript of the plant to Kew, as I had no male flowers, thinking that there might have been such an other specimens of Drummonds there. I have never receive others since, but reexamining the specimens returned by you, I find all my former observations confirmed. I enclose the copy of my manuscript made by Mr Th Müller at the time,<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS not found.</p>
               </note> who returned several years ago to Europe. Probably I should never have looked on the plant again, had I not received a genuine new Threlkeldia with flowers three times as long as in T. diffusa from Queensland and this brought me back to my <name key="Trematocarya">Trematocarya</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">See M to G. Bentham, 27 February 1869.</p>
               </note> of former years.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Having meanwhile applied the same name to a fossil genus,<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M erected <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Trematocaryon </seg>(<seg style="font-style: italic; ">T. mclellani</seg>) in B71.05.02, p. 48.</p>
               </note> I have called the new Phytolaccaceous plant <name key="Cypselocarpus%20haloragoides">Cypselocarpus haloragoides</name>.<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B73.04.02, p. 36; see comments under <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Threlkeldia%20haloragoides">Threlkeldia haloragoides</name>
                     </seg> in Bentham (1863-78), vol. 5, p. 198.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The curious <name key="Hemichroa%20mesembryanthema">Hemichroa mesembryanthema</name> will also interest you. Like <name key="Kochia%20oppositifolia">Kochia oppositifolia</name> it has the leaves opposed. I have sent the plant to Kew. The new <name key="Kochia%20dichoptera">Kochia dichoptera</name> has <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">5</hi>
               </seg> additional <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">vertical</hi>
               </seg> wings! The fruit of <name key="Cadellia%20monostylis">Cadellia monostylis</name> proves that plant to be very distinct as a genus. I have named it Guilfoylia in honor of the sender of the fruit.<note xml:id="ftn9" type="footnote" n="9">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">M erected <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Guilfoylia</seg> (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">G. monostylis</seg>) in B73.04.02, p. 34, eponymizing W. Guilfoyle. Bentham's description as <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Cadellia%20monostylis">Cadellia monostylis</name>
                     </seg> has no description of the fruit (Bentham (1863-78), vol. 1, p. 375).</p>
               </note> You may find other notes of interest in the new fragmenta, the work after a whole years cessation being at last resumed, amidst continued combat for existence of myself!</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">With profound regards</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Always your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">I find <name key="Monochoria%20cyanea">Monochoria cyanea</name> quite distinct from M vaginalis</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I look forward with intense interest to the new volume of the genera also to the vol VI of the Flora.<note xml:id="ftn10" type="footnote" n="10">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83), vol. 2, part 1; Bentham (1863-78), vol. 6. </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
